accessibility.text: How many icebergs did we melt air freighting our printers from Shenzhen?
We have haven’t been driving anywhere so it’s all even
Please is there a prefered mac iOS Slicer to use with the Ender 3 Pro? It appears that Rhino has a slicer for Windows.
For starters, I'd recommend Cura, as there are many predefined printers that you can simply import with their own printer-specific settings.
My corners started peeling up mid build. Any recommendations on setting changes or best practices?

Most likely cause, at least in my experience, would be that the nozzle is too far from the print bed. If room temperature is varying a lot (printer is by a fan/vent/window/door) the temperature change could be a cause as well.
Thx Robert. I’ll check my nozzle gap. Maybe print on a raft would help?
Cyrus, If I’m hearing you correctly, your Y axis is not working? Therefore we need to troubleshoot the movement of the print bed?
Thanks for looking at this @kevin philbin, but the elephant printed correctly and I have no issues printing the test pattern you posted. So I'm not sure why it's okay in some cases and not other ones

I’m getting closer! But still had some issues. I ran the clean calibration test then immediately ran the panther print.  Anyone have thoughts about what could help with the loose spaghetti? I’m extruding at 200c and bed is at 50c. Thx!
please any thoughts on how to improve?
@kevin philbin, not ready to call it fully tested, but firmware upgrade seems to have resolved all my issues! More to come on this soon; test should be done in 3-4 hrs …
loose spaghetti can also come from how you slice
Thx! I’ll look into slicing setting adjustments.
Update first test looks great!!! I fell asleep and running the second test now
One negative thing that stood out is the new firmware slowing down the prints (edited)
Please help with STL export. I’ve tried a few settings but it appears I’m missing something. (edited)

Some things to check: did you BooleanUnion everything in Rhino so that it’s a single closed polysurface? Also can you try loading this in Cura or slic3r or another slicer? It’s kind of hard to see what’s going on with MacOS’s default STL previewer
It's also a little difficult to tell from the screen shot, if the cutting edge is capped/solid or not.
happy to. lemme check Jasper and Victor’s points and i’ll post it. thx for looking.
@Victor Allen Good point. Cutting edge was not capped.
I tried cap command then selected both extrusions but then it filled across entire plane. Please do know how to cap just between my to extruded walls?

i made a quick video for you.  no sound sorry.  delete the extrusion with a right to left selection.  use extrude curve and make sure you select the solid option. the extrude outer curves the ame way and then boolean union. sending video link in a minute
ok thx. I’ll check that too.
Been crashing a bunch! Having issues with saving and permissions. So I’m delaying in posting the file.
My prints are off by 5mm on the Z axis. Is this All3dp.com calibration    workflow the right approach?
wait, 5mm? Hmm, that sounds like more than tuning the extruder would fix. In your Ender3 menu settings, what is the Z steps-per-mm?
Thx for chiming in . I’ll take a look.
Hey Kevin, you might be skipping z-steps. Make sure your coupler on the lead screw is tight!
Ok 400 is correct (for ender3). Looking at your part, the first half (in Z) looks rather squished. @Paige Johnson is right. Check those screws! (edited)
Ok checked and snugged! Thx for the fast response @JoshuaV @Paige Johnson
Hmm, something on the Z axis may be binding.
Your first layer with brim looks great.
And your previous pic looked fine in XY
I had to reassemble mine a few times as it was binding make sure the brass screws on the thing that attaches to the extruder is not too tight

Here's one suggestion for debugging: unscrew the coupler from the leadscrew. You should now be able to freely move the y axis up and down with your hand (and the leadscrew will come with it). By hand, move it up-and-down. Does it bind? If so, you may need to loosen-and-readjust some parts of the Y axis (Step 6) until they slide smoothly.
Also check page 3 of this to see if your motor is holding the leadscrew at an angle.
Great input. I’ll get to it. Thx @JoshuaV and @Vincent

Possibly had small bind from misalignment and/or over tightening bearings. Easy to feel when taking off leadscrew coupler. I adjusted z axis struts, bearings, realigned Z motor, rebalanced feet and top brace.
Some of the smaller screws had loosened up on the extruder and Y-axis.

That was my life entire last night. Assuming it's unintentional spaghetti (), try leveling the bed. It took me multiple tries to get it right. Honestly not sure if I still do have it \"right\"! (edited)
